					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I can answer what I can, and leave the rest to others.<br /><br />1. In the ROM image, CHR-ROM is placed after PRG-ROM. When executing, CHR-ROM is permanently mapped to PPU $0000-$1FFF as much as PRG-ROM is mapped to CPU $8000-$FFFF.<br /><br />3. Most games reserve a page (256 bytes) of CPU RAM and write the high byte of that page to $4014.<br /><br />5. Not unless you are doing PPU operations mid rendering (like a status bar split with a sprite 0 hit). For simple PPU operations in vblank you have about 2250 cycles from a NMI to do whatever.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

